<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/ipcc-release-major-climate-change-report-tomorrow-194651079.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/QQGpZEJA_REowDXnxi7sAA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_US/News/LiveScience.com/air-pollution-110224-02.jpg1348180509" width="130" height="86" alt="IPCC to Release Major Climate Change Report Tomorrow" align="left" title="IPCC to Release Major Climate Change Report Tomorrow" border="0" /></a>The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), an organization created by the United Nations to assess the state and science of global warming, will release part of its newest major report tomorrow (Sept. 27).</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://theweek.com/article/index/250284/chinas-newest-environmental-disaster' target="_blank">China's newest environmental disaster</a><br />
So much for China's change of heart when it comes to taking care of the environment.The Chinese government recently approved construction on nine of 40 large-scale plants that will convert coal into synthetic natural gas — a process that produces seven times more greenhouse gas emissions than regular natural gas production, and uses as much as 100 times the water as shale gas extraction, according to a new study by Duke University.The research, published in the peer-reviewed journal Nature Climate Change, comes just two weeks after China announced plans to cut down on air pollution, and
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/u-n-scientists-aim-pitch-climate-case-widest-185709747.html' target="_blank">U.N. scientists aim to pitch climate case to widest audience</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/u-n-scientists-aim-pitch-climate-case-widest-185709747.html"><img src="http://l.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/IvZ50xXqhLf0rtZHkuKCcg--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-26T190327Z_3_CBRE98P1GSP00_RTROPTP_2_SWEDEN.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="Sweden&#039;s Environment Minister Ek and Stocker, a member of an UN IPCC, attend an IPCC meeting in Stockholm" align="left" title="Sweden&#039;s Environment Minister Ek and Stocker, a member of an UN IPCC, attend an IPCC meeting in Stockholm" border="0" /></a>By Environment Correspondent Alister Doyle STOCKHOLM (Reuters) - A U.N. panel of global climate scientists were set to work through Thursday night to ensure that their strongest case yet for man-made global warming would make sense to the widest possible audience. Drafts show that the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) is set to pronounce that most of the warming of the Earth&#039;s surface since the 1950s is &quot;extremely likely&quot; -- at least 95 percent probable -- to be man-made. At its last meeting in 2007, it put the probability at 90 percent, and in 2001 it was 66 percent. </p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/climate-change-could-mercury-pollution-worse-180620387.html' target="_blank">How Climate Change Could Make Mercury Pollution Worse</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/climate-change-could-mercury-pollution-worse-180620387.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/nrFvtoQVP6RXXkwmHqAE8g--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_US/News/LiveScience.com/Wildfire-grass.jpg1380218560" width="130" height="86" alt="How Climate Change Could Make Mercury Pollution Worse" align="left" title="How Climate Change Could Make Mercury Pollution Worse" border="0" /></a>Mercury pollution and climate change are both unintended consequences of burning fossil fuels for centuries. A new study finds another link between the two problems: Climate change has the potential to make mercury pollution worse.</p><br clear="all"/>
