<p><a href="http://www.theverge.com/2013/9/25/4770342/twitter-alerts-offer-push-notifications-text-messages-in-emergencies"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/waTzK4x6FCnixVrjepVAvg--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_US/News/The%20Verge/Screen_Shot_2012-10-29_at_11.11.01_AM_large.png" width="130" height="86" alt="Twitter turns its social messaging platform into an emergency alert system" align="left" title="Twitter turns its social messaging platform into an emergency alert system" border="0" /></a>Building on previous disaster response efforts, Twitter is rolling out a feature that will let agencies broadcast messages in a crisis. The program, called simply Twitter Alerts, lets users sign up for emergency messages from agencies like FEMA, the World Health Organization, and local police departments. Once you opt into an individual organization&#039;s alerts, it can send you push notifications and text messages in case of an emergency, like a less formal version of the severe weather warnings the National Weather Service sends straight to smartphones. </p><br clear="all"/>
